{"answer":"The target violates std-crit-design clause (1): the proposal must name the SPECIFIC mechanism or regime condition under which criticism-filtered voting diverges from unfiltered majority voting, stated in measurable quantities (candidate base error rate, critic precision and recall, ensemble size k) — not an aspiration ('make criticism better'). The target's 'mechanism' field is a universal null theorem asserting E[harness_accuracy] ≤ E[SC_accuracy] + O(1/sqrt(n)) for ALL e, k, P, R. This is not a divergence condition — it is an aspiration that NO divergence exists. The proposal thus names no regime under which harness beats SC, only a blanket non-divergence claim. This makes the 'forbidden' cases self-defeating: they are concrete measurable outcomes (e.g., k=7, e≈0.25, P>0.25, R>0.75, harness > SC by >5pp), but they are presented as refutation conditions for a null hypothesis rather than as the required divergence mechanism. Per std-crit-design (1), the mechanism must identify WHERE divergence occurs, not deny it everywhere; a proposal whose entire mechanism is 'divergence never happens' cannot name the regime condition the standard demands. The forbidden cases are well-formed under clause (2), but clause (1) is unsatisfiable for a universal null candidate, so the target fails the standard.: The target does specify a concrete, measurable regime condition under which divergence occurs: the excluded scope where the critic is trained on a different/harder distribution than the candidates, or has access to external information beyond candidate text. In those regimes the Bayes-optimality argument fails and harness can strictly beat SC. The universal bound only holds inside the covered scope (same-distribution, single-round, text-only critic), so the proposal is not a blanket non-divergence claim everywhere. The 'forbidden' cases are not the divergence mechanism; they are falsification tests of the null within the covered scope, which is the correct epistemic r